Carnivores: Modders Edition - Manual

Beta v1.0.5

>

Introduction

Thank you for downloading Carnivores Modders Edition. This patch aims to create a more flexible engine so mod-creators can build more detailed and varied mod packs than ever before.

Planned future features are listed here.

Change Log v1.0.5

  • New spawngroup system offers completely flexible spawning rules.
  • A creature can now be set to respond to a specific call.
  • Overwrite if a creature is selected from the menu.
Note: As of 1.0.5, AI should be used to set a creatures AI, not Clone.

Note: As of 1.0.5, all creatures are defined within the characters section of the _RES.

Note: As of 1.0.5, radar should now be set to TRUE or FALSE (a char overwrite can be used for huntables).

Note: As of 1.0.5, fearCall should now use numbers 0-8 (or 0-9) to specify which call to fear.

Note: As of 1.0.5, all creatures need a hearK value to react to gunshots (default 0.5).
Note: An account must be created with the Carn2 menu before you can run survival mode.

Note: Save files from Modders Edition 1.0.3 or prior or vanilla Carnivores 2 are not compatible with this version.

Note: smell, hear and look in the RES have been renamed to smellK, hearK and lookK

Bug Fixes v1.0.5

  • Creatures can now hear.

All known bugs for 1.0.5 are listed here.

Carnivores Modders Edition is still in beta and everything is subject to change. If you wish to report a bug not listed in the spreadsheet, or have any suggestions or queries, contact Ornithomimid 1 on the Carnivores Saga Discord channel or via the Carnivores Saga forums.

Features

  • 10th huntable slot
  • AI can be reordered or duplicated throughout the roster
  • 108 map ambient slots per area
  • 128 trophy slots
  • All huntable herbivore AI can be made dangerous
  • All huntable carnivore AI can be made non-dangerous
  • Any AI creature can be spawned as map ambients
  • Set which creatures can random spawn
  • Pachycephalosaurus AI
  • All Ice Age AI
  • Dangerous brachiosaurus AI
  • (Dangerous) land brachiosaurus AI
  • Ichthyornis AI
  • Fish AI
  • Mosasaurus AI
  • Fully customisable spawning rules for all creatures
  • Fish/mosasaurus AI can be made dangerous/non-dangerous
  • Swimming can be added to ambient creatures
  • Swimming can be added to huntable herbivores
  • Swimming can be disabled for carnivores
  • Manually set how high each creature swims in the water
  • Pack/herding AI can be added to any AI
  • Pack max/min size and density can be customised
  • Speed patch
  • Aggression patch
  • Unlimited triangle count on Creature and Weapon models
  • Changeable animation order for all AI
  • Up to 32 Idle animations for fish/mosasaurus ai creatures
  • 32 custom idle groups per creature (except fish/mosasaurus ai)
  • Up to 32 Idle animations per idle group
  • Up to 32 custom kill animations / hunter death animations per creature
  • Up to 32 death animations per creature
  • Up to 32 roar animations per creature (t-rex AI creatures only)
  • Up to 32 look animations per creature (t-rex AI creatures only)
  • Up to 32 smell animations per creature (t-rex AI creatures only)
  • Up to 32 water idle animations per creature (ichthyornis AI creatures only)
  • Up to 32 water death animations per creature (dimorphodon/pteranodon/ichthyornis AI creatures only)
  • Creatures showing on radar can be individually toggled
  • Set radar colour for creatures
  • Set blood colour for creatures
  • Option to disable bending for creatures
  • Option to disable/enable weaving for all creatures
  • Customise the weaving range for creatures
  • Option to make creatures aggressive only after being shot
  • Option to make creatures always flee after being shot
  • Option to make creatures flee if it hears gunshots regardless of aggression
  • Hide a creatures stats in the binoculars
  • Set which creatures can be added to the trophy room
  • Kill animations can be changed to only play once, instead of looping.
  • Change which dinos run from certain calls
  • Custom spawn regions per map
  • Spawn max/min and spawnrate per map (minimum spawn rate of 1/1000 chance per hunt)
  • Creatures can be set to never leave certain regions unless chased/lured out.
  • Creatures can be set to avoid specific areas per map.
  • Minimum/maximum depth (fish/mosasaurus AI creatures only)
  • Minimum/maximum altitude for flier AI creatures
  • New overwrite system - Any RES value can be adjusted depending on map, time of day, creature selected or a combination
  • New Primal Prey style trophy room system.
  • Trophies can be animated (res togglable)
  • Jump range for mosasaurus ai
  • Toggle crouch.
  • Customisable snow/weather settings for each map
  • Customisable survival mode

Getting Started

Before starting the game, complete the following steps:

  1. Installation

    To install Carnivores Modders Edition, you must have a vanilla copy of Carnivores 2 (always make a backup first!). Copy and paste the contents of the Carnivores 2 folder onto your vanilla copy of the game overwriting any existing files.

  2. Map Ambient Demo 2

    The Map Ambient Demo is a showcase of some of the features used in Carnivores Modders Edition including:

    • Pack hunting velociraptors.
    • Rare-spawning huntable Pachycephalosaurus.
    • Rare-spawning huntable Triceratops.
    • Ambient Icthyornis (spawns in flocks of around the coast).
    • Ambient Mosasaurus that spawns along the coast of Delpheous Hills.
    • Ambient Climatius (fish that spawns in deep ocean on Delpheous Hills).
    • Ambient Parexus (fish that spawns in the shallows around the estuary on the west side of Delpheous Hills).
    • Ambient Pink Parexus (fish that spawns in the pond on the northeast side of Delpheous Hills).

    To install the map ambient demo, copy the contents of the "Map Ambient Demo 2\HUNTDAT" folder onto your copy of Carnivores Modders Edition and overwriting any existing files.

    Note: Ichthyornis & Brachiosaurus will be updated with more animations/sounds in the next update and currently use some placeholder animations.

  3. Compatibility Mode

    Right click on CARN2.exe and click properties. On the compatability tab, check the box "Run this program in compatability mode" and select "Windows 98", then click ok.

  4. Driver Settings

    In the game settings, the audio driver must be set to "Direct Sound 3D", and graphics must be set to "Software" or "3DFX Glide" (this will be set automatically).

    If using 3DFX Glide (recommended), you will need to install nGlide if you haven't done so already - this is a one-time install so you won't need to repeat this when installing future versions of Carnivores Modders Edition.

    Download and install the latest version of nGlide here.

    Once installed, navigate to C:\ProgramData\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\nGlide and open the nGlide Configurator.

    Make sure the settings match those shown here, then click apply.

    You may also need to adjust the resolution in the game settings.

  5. Error fixes:

    If encounter this error on 3DFX Graphics, download and install the Visual C++ Redistributable (x64) here.

Creating a custom survival mode

See below for a list of res values to create a custom survival mode:

See subsequent sections of the manual for more detail.

  • You can set area, weapon and time of day in the common section of the res.
  • You can set the hunters position and the spawn location of creature waves in the areatable section of the res. These values must be in the corresponding area res entry.
  • You can set which creatures spawn and in which order by assigning a survivalIndex to the creatures res entry. The first creature must be indexed 1, then 2 etc. Survival mode can handle up to 128 creature varieties but you cannot skip indexes.

>

_RES Editing - common

This res section is for universal game settings.

>

_RES value: survivalArea

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the area for survival mode.

>

_RES value: survivalWeapon

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the weapon for survival mode.

>

_RES value: survivalDTM

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the time of day for survival mode (0 = dawn, 1 = day, 2 = night).

>

_RES Editing - areatable

Each entry in the areatable section of the _RES sets the weather and survival location for the respective area (an entry is required for every area).

Below are the values that can be used to set weather as well as some presets to demonstrate the types of effect that can be achieved.

Note: Weather particles are not rendered in software mode.

>

example preset: Ice Age snow

snow1 = TRUE
hSpd = 4
vSpd = 192
dens = 2000
red1 = 240
gre1 = 240
blu1 = 240
alp1 = 255
rad1 = 1

>

example preset: Rain storm

snow1 = TRUE
snow2 = TRUE
hSpd = 200
vSpd = 5000
dens = 16000
red1 = 179
gre1 = 211
blu1 = 211
alp1 = 136
rad1 = 0.5
red2 = 179
gre2 = 211
blu2 = 211
alp2 = 5
rad2 = 20

>

example preset: Sand storm

snow1 = TRUE
hSpd = 200
vSpd = 192
dens = 2000
red1 = 168
gre1 = 132
blu1 = 97
alp1 = 25
rad1 = 200


>

_RES value: snow1

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

When set to true, snow/rain will be spawned on the map. When set to false (or not defined) no weather effects will be created.

Note: Setting this value to true will not automatically add Ice Age snow to the map unless the other values are properly configured, see the Ice Age snow preset above.

>

_RES value: snow2

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

When set to true, a second particle is added to each snowdrop which can be configured individually.

>

_RES value: vSpd

Data type: Whole Number

The vertical speed that snow particles fall.

>

_RES value: hSpd

Data type: Whole Number

The horizontal speed of snow particles.

Note: speed and direction is effected by the wind.

>

_RES value: dens

Data type: Whole Number

The number of snow particles rendered at any time.

Note: cannot exceed 16000.

>

_RES value: red1/red2, gre1/gre2, blu1/blu2

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the colour of snow particles (RGB 0-255).
Only use red2, gre2 & blu2 to define the colour of the second particle if snow2 is set to TRUE.

>

_RES value: alp1/alp2

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the opacity of snow particles (0-255).
Only use alp2 to define the opacity of second particle if snow2 is set to TRUE.

>

_RES value: rad1/rad2

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the radius of snow particles.
Only use rad2 to define the radius of the second particle if snow2 is set to TRUE.


>

_RES value: survivalPlayerX survivalPlayerY

Data type: Whole Number

The xy position of the player in survival mode.

Note: It's recommended to open the map in Alt Editor 2, and use the mouse cursor to find the coordinates for these values.

Vanilla Value (Mount Ravan)
survivalPlayerX
345
survivalPlayerY
245

>

_RES value: survivalPlayerA

Data type: Whole Number

The initial rotation of the player in survival mode (in degrees).

Vanilla Value (Mount Ravan)
survivalPlayerA
345

>

_RES value: survivalDinoXMin survivalDinoXMax survivalDinoYMin survivalDinoYMax

Data type: Whole Number

The region where waves of creatures spawn in survival mode.
These four values control the four corners of the spawn region (xmin,ymin is the top left corner, xmax,ymax is the bottom right corner).

Note: It's recommended to open the map in Alt Editor 2, and use the mouse cursor to find the coordinates for these values.

Vanilla Value (Mount Ravan)
survivalDinoXMin
318
survivalDinoXMax
336
survivalDinoYMin
170
survivalDinoYMax
180

_RES Editing - spawntable

Each entry in the spawntable section of the _RES area defines a set of spawning rules (a spawngroup). The game can have up to 64 spawngroups.
For example, below are the spawngroups for vanilla Carnivores 2.

Creatures can be assigned to spawngroups individually using the spawninfo section in their _RES entries.

>

_RES value: spawnmin

Data type: Whole Number

The minimum number of creatures that will spawn per hunt.

>

_RES value: spawnmax

Data type: Whole Number

The maximum number of creatures that can spawn per hunt.

Note: Each hunt can handle up to 255 creatures in total.

>

_RES value: spawnrate

Data type: Decimal Number

A value between 0 and 1, the chance of each creature spawning. 0 means the spawnmin will always be spawned 1 means the spawnmax will always be spawned. The smallest permitted probability is 0.001.

>

_RES value: densityMulti

Data type: Whole Number

Determines the influence of the density setting from the options screen. If set to 0, the density setting will have no effect on this spawngroup.

If the density setting is left as default (50%) it will not impact any spawngroup. If the density setting is set to 100%, then the spawn count for the spawngroup will be increased by the whole value of densityMulti. If the density setting is set to 0%, then the spawn count for the spawngroup will be reduced by the whole value of densityMulti. e.g. in the above screenshot, the maximum density setting will cause 2 extra ambients to spawn and 4 extra huntables to spawn.

>

_RES value: moveForward

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set to true, creatures will spawn within the hunters view range, and will respawn if killed or if they move too far from the hunter. This feature is compatible with regions/avoidances.
This option is useful to give the impression that the entire map is populated by an ambient creature while saving processing time.

Note: pack hunting cannot be used when moveForward is enabled.

>

_RES value: randomise

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set to true, each spawned creature will be randomly selected from the creatures assigned to the group. Otherwise they will be spawned in sequential order.

For example, if Parasaurolophus, Ankylosaurus and Stegosaurus are selected from the hunt menu, they will spawn as:

  1. Parasaurolophus
  2. Ankylosaurus
  3. Stegosaurus
  4. Parasaurolophus
  5. Ankylosaurus
  6. Stegosaurus
    7. ...

but if randomise is true, they will spawn in a random order e.g.

  1. Parasaurolophus
  2. Parasaurolophus
  3. Parasaurolophus
  4. Ankylosaurus
  5. Stegosaurus
  6. Ankylosaurus
    7. ...

Note: If randomise is set to true, then the number of each creature spawned will be uneven, or one of the creatures may not be spawned at all.

Note: If randomise is set to false and the spawnmax is lower than the number of creatures assigned to the group, then only the first assigned creatures will always spawn.

>

_RES Subsection: region

Defines an area that creatures must spawn in. Each spawngroup can have up to 16 regions per map. If none are defined, the creatures will spawn anywhere on the map.

>

_RES value: xmax, xmin, ymax, ymin

Data type: Whole Number

Regions are square. These four values control the four corners of the spawn region (xmin,ymin is the top left corner, xmax,ymax is the bottom right corner).

Note: It's recommended to open the map in Alt Editor 2, and use the mouse cursor to find the coordinates for these values.

>

_RES Subsection: avoid

Defines an area that creatures cannot spawn in nor enter. Each spawngroup can have up to 16 avoidance regions per map.

>

_RES value: xmax, xmin, ymax, ymin

Data type: Whole Number

Avoid regions are square. These four values control the four corners of the spawn region (xmin,ymin is the top left corner, xmax,ymax is the bottom right corner).

Note: It's recommended to open the map in Alt Editor 2, and use the mouse cursor to find the coordinates for these values.

>

overwrite and addition

Overwrite

An overwrite is used to change any _RES value depending on the area, time of day and creature(s) selected from the hunt menu. This can be used to change the name, CAR file, ai etc.

The below example changes the parasaurs CAR file on Fort Ciskin. Make sure to include the opening and closing brackets and don't leave any blank lines.

The below example changes the parasaurs CAR file at night.

  • time0 = dawn
  • time1 = day
  • time2 = night
Note: The second overwrite statement takes precedent over the first, so the night CAR file will be used at night, even on Fort Ciskin.

The below example only changes the parasaurs CAR file if Fort Ciskin AND night mode are selected.

The below example changes the file if either the 1st, 2nd or 3rd area AND dawn or day is selected.

The below example shows how char overwrite is used for Parasaurolophus spawning in Carnivores 2.

  • char0 = Parasaurolophus selected in menu.
  • char1 = Ankylosaurus selected in menu.
  • char2 = Stegosaurus selected in menu.
    • etc

The Parasaurolophus is only added to spawn group 2 and shown on radar if selected from the menu, but can randomly spawn regardless. char can be used with area and time, and can be defined multiple times in an overwrite for different selected creatures.

_RES value: dontFear

Data type: Whole Number

This will undo a fearCall statement, e.g. the following will make a creature no longer fear t-rex calls at night:

fearCall = 18
overwrite time2 {
dontFear = 18
}

>

_RES value: canswim

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

Setting this to true allows the creature to swim. This cannot be applied to classic brachiosaurus, dangerous brachiosaurus, ichthyornis, fish or mosasaurus AI creatures. Setting canswim to true for land brachiosaurus AI will allow it to also wade into the water like a standard brachiosaurus.

Note: if canswim is true, you must also set waterLevel (see below).
Note: Creatures that can swim must also have swimAnim and swmspd.

>

_RES value: waterLevel

Data type: Whole Number

Sets the height the creature swims in the water (not incuding waterLevel or setting it to 0 will cause creatures to "walk on water"). If using waterDAnim for pterodon/dimorphodon AI, then waterLevel can be used to define how deep the water has to be to play the animation. If using land brachiosaurus AI with canswim, then waterLevel is used to set how deep it can wade into the water.

Note: Not applicable to fish/mosasaurus/trex ai.

_RES value: fearShotHear

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set the true, the creature will flee if it hears gunshots, regardless of the creatures aggression value.

Note: Not applicable to fish/mosasaurus/trex ai.

>

_RES value: HideBinoc

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

When set to true, the creature's stats will not appear in the binoculars.

>

_RES value: trophy

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

When set to true the creatures you kill will be added to the trophy room.

Note: score can only only be earned if trophy is set to TRUE.

Note: no more than 128 types of creature can be added to the trophy room.

Note: as of 1.0.3 a tropinfo section is also required.

>

_RES value: packMax

Data type: Whole Number

The maximum number of creatures that can spawn per pack/herd.

Note: Packing cannot be used with a moveForward spawngroup.

>

_RES value: packMin

Data type: Whole Number

The minimum number of creatures that can spawn per pack/herd.

Note: Packing cannot be used with a moveForward spawngroup.

>

_RES value: packDensity

Data type: Whole Number

This value controls how closely a pack/herd stick together (25 is the example value used for velociraptor).

Note: Packing cannot be used with a moveForward spawngroup.

>

_RES value: survivalIndex

Data type: Whole Number

Creatures with a survival index will spawn in survival mode.
The first creature to spawn should have a survival index of 1, the second 2 etc. Survival mode can have between 1 and 128 types of creature.

Note: No numbers should be skipped over.

When set to 0, the brachiosaurus will ignore all terrain. 128 is recommended for brachiosaurus, but if you place a smaller creature on brachiosaurus AI, then this value should be set to 64.

>

_RES value: anim

Data type: Whole Number

Position of an idle animation in the CAR file (starting from 0).

Each idlegroup can have up to 32 animations. These will be played in a random sequence.

>

_RES value: startChance

Data type: Decimal Number

The probability (after every walk cycle) that the idle group will start playing.

The value should be between 0 (never) and 1 (constant).

>

_RES value: endChance

Data type: Decimal Number

The probability that the idle group will stop playing. This probability will only be checked after playing the last-defined idle animation in the group or, if randomEnding is TRUE, after playing any idle animation in the group.

The value should be between 0 (never) and 1 (always).

>

_RES value: randomStarting

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set to true, then the first idle animation in the group will be randomised. Otherwise the first animation played in the group will always be the first defined-animation in the group.

>

_RES value: randomEnding

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set to true, then the idle sequence has a chance to end after each animation. Otherwise the sequence only has a chance to end after playing the last-defined idle animation in the group.

>

_RES value: instantRepeat

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set to true, then there is a chance for another idle sequence to start immediately after the idle group ends. Otherwise the creature will play at least one walk cycle before it has a chance to enter another idle sequence.

>

_RES Subsection: waterIgroup

Note: Icthyornis AI only

Defines a group of swimming idle animations that will play in a random sequence.

This subsection can be defined multiple times. Each creature can have up to 32 water idle groups. Each water idle group can contain up to 32 animations or just a single animation. See Idle Group (above) for res values that can be defined inside this subsection.

>

_RES Subsection: deathtype

Defines the death animations for a creature.

This subsection can be defined multiple times, a deathType will be randomly picked when the creature dies. Each creature can have up to 32 deathTypes, and must have at least 1 (except fish and mosasaurus AI).

>

_RES value: dieAnim

Data type: Whole Number

Position of a death animation in the CAR file (starting from 0).

AI

_RES Subsection: killtype

Defines the kill information for a creature.

This subsection can be defined multiple times, a killType will be randomly picked when the creature kills the hunter. Each creature can have up to 32 killTypes. If a creatures has no killTypes, it will just run over the hunter like the vanilla chasmosaurus.

_RES value: hunterSync

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

Set this to true for custom kill animations where the hunter and creature models need to be in-sync, e.g. the T-Rex kill animation.

Note: hunterOffset will always equal 0 if hunterSync is turned on.

Note: recommended for fish/mosasaurus AI creatures.

>

_RES value: dontloop

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If you set this to true, the creature will only play the kill/eat animation once before walking off.

>

_RES value: carryCorpse

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If you set this to true, the creature will carry the hunter's corpse after playing the kill animation.

Note: dontloop and hunterSync must also be set to TRUE.

>

_RES value: hunterCarryAnim

Data type: Whole Number

If dontloop and carryCorpse are both set to true, the creature will walk away carrying the hunters corpse. hunterCarryAnim is the hunter's animation as they are being carried. It must have the same frame count and KPS as the creatures walkAnim.

AI
Vanilla Value
Mosasaurus
6

>

_RES value: scream

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If you set this to true, HUM_DIE.WAV will play when the hunter is killed.

>

_RES Subsection: spawninfo

This subsection is used to add a creature to spawngroup. Any creature without spawninfo cannot spawn. Each creature can have up to 32 spawninfo.

Note: you can spawn in huntables selected from the menu by surrounding the spawninfo with a character overwrite (see the overwrite section of the manual).

>

_RES value: spawngroup

Data type: Whole Number

The spawngroup to add the creature to (spawngroups are numbered starting from 0).

>

_RES Subsection: tropinfo

Defines the position of a creature's trophy in the trophy room.

This subsection can be defined multiple times per creature for each trophy position. Each creature can have up to 32 trophy positions.

Note: Currently, the trophy room can only hold 128 trophies total.

Note: Currently, new trophies will not replace existing trophies if all the trophy positions are full.

Note: trophy = TRUE is also required (outside the tropinfo subsection).

>

_RES value: tropAnim

Data type: Whole Number

Position of the trophy animation in the CAR file (starting from 0).

>

_RES value: playAnim

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

If set to true, the trophy animation will play.

>

_RES value: tropPos

Data type: Whole Number

Trophies spawn on the map relative to a spawn point position. This number controls which spawn point the trophy will spawn at (starting from 0).

>

_RES value: xoffset, yoffset, zoffset

Data type: Whole Number

These three values move the trophy relative to the spawn point (tropPos) (y is vertical).

>

_RES value: xscale, yscale, zscale

Data type: Whole Number

These three values adjust the trophy position based on the creatures scale (y is vertical). If the creature is the maximum size the entire value will be added, if the creature is the minimum size then nothing will be added. These values will default to 0 if not set.

Note: Changing a creatures scaleA and scale0 will effect the trophy position if x/y/zscale is greater than 0.

>

_RES value: xdata, ydata, zdata

Data type: Whole Number

These three values set the position the player must stand to show the trophy information, relative to the spawn point (tropPos) (y is vertical).

>

_RES value: alpha, beta, gamma

Data type: Whole Number

These three values set the rotation of the trophy in degrees.

Water Particle Effects

Fish/mosasaurus AI only. Water particle effects are used to make splashes when a mosasaurus AI creature jumps from the water, or when a fish or mosasaurus comes to the surface to play an idle animation. The particle values for the animation should be defined directly after a fishIdleAnim or jumpAnim value. See the below example for the mosasaurus jumping and idle animation values.

Vanilla Values
Jump
jumpAnim = 3
jmpspd = 1.0
jumpPartFrame1 = 1
jumpPartFrame2 = 11
jumpPartDist = 240
jumpPartCnt = 500
jumpPartMag = 40
jumpPartAngled = TRUE
jumpPartCircle = TRUE
Idle
fishIdleAnim = 4
idlePartFrame1 = 12
idlePartFrame2 = 13
idlePartDist = 22
idlePartCnt = 3
idlePartMag = 20
idlePartOffset = 320

These values set how particles are generated for each frame of the animation.

Note: Excessive use of particles could cause the game to lag or crash.

Note: Some particle values are affected by the creatures scale, so make sure to test thoroughly.

>

_RES value: jumpPartFrame1 / idlePartFrame1

Data type: Whole Number

The first frame of the animation (start counting from frame 0) where particles are generated.

>

_RES value: jumpPartFrame2 / idlePartFrame2

Data type: Whole Number

The last frame of the animation (start counting from frame 0) where particles are generated.

>

_RES value: jumpPartCnt / idlePartCnt

Data type: Whole Number

The number of particles generated per frame.

>

_RES value: jumpPartDist / idlePartDist

Data type: Whole Number

The maximum distance particles are generated from the creatures position.

>

_RES value: jumpPartMag / idlePartMag

Data type: Whole Number

The height of the particle splash.

>

_RES value: jumpPartOffset / idlePartOffset

Data type: Whole Number

Increasing this value shifts the particle effect forward towards the front of the creature.

>

_RES value: jumpPartAngled / idlePartAngled

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

Setting this to true will angle the splash particles to move forward with the creature, otherwise the splashes will shoot straight up.

>

_RES value: jumpPartCircle / idlePartCircle

Data type: TRUE/FALSE

Setting this is to true will add water circles for each particle generated.

Note: When the particles fall back into the water, they will also generate circles.
